<media id="fs-idm85766432" alt=" Photo shows a bee collecting nectar from a flower.">
<image mime-type="image/jpg" src="Figure_20_00_01.jpg" width="600"/>
</media>
<caption>The life of a bee is very different from the life of a flower, but the two organisms are related. Both are members the domain Eukarya and have cells containing many similar organelles, genes, and proteins. (credit: modification of work by John Beetham)</caption>
</figure>
<para id="fs-idm142425376">This bee and <emphasis effect="italics">Echinacea</emphasis> flower (<link target-id="fig-ch20_00_01" document=""/>) could not look more different, yet they are related, as are all living organisms on Earth. By following pathways of similarities and changes&#8212;both visible and genetic&#8212;scientists seek to map the evolutionary past of how life developed from single-celled organisms to the tremendous collection of creatures that have germinated, crawled, floated, swam, flown, and walked on this planet.</para>
